ia – Voyages into the Unexpected -- tRe-Enacting the Arctic Voyage: The Northwest Passage in British Literature -- tReflections at Home: Canada in the View of Recent European Writers -- tStuffed Mooseheads: Canada as (Missing) Cliché in European Theatre -- tCultural Reductionism and the Reception of Canadian Literature in Germany -- tWildlife Abounds? The Photographic Deconstruction of a Canadian Cliché in Robert Gernhardt’s Satire “Blanket Creek oder Verwilderte Wünsche” -- t“One Sees Only What One Knows”: German Popular Literature and its Images of Canada -- tCanada as a Role Model? Reflections of a Country in Post-War German Youth Fiction -- tWhat makes a Canadian? Strategies of Presenting Canadianness in Teaching Materials -- tList of Contributors -- t302-3040 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEver since the first exploratory expeditions in the early modern period, North America has epitomized to Europeans a promise and the hope for the fulfilment of great expectations, be it of more freedom, greater wealth, social liberation or religious tolerance. While numerous features in this dialogic intercontinental relationship will hold true for North America in its entirety, the vast northern territories which we know as Canada today began to emerge early on as a specific iconic location in European mind-maps, and they definitely acquired a distinctive profile after the formation of the USA. As a rich source of cultural exchange and an important partner in political and economic cooperation Canada has come to occupy an important position in the cultural discourses of many European nations. It is these refractions and images of Canada which this volume thoroughly explores in European literature and culture. The contributions include literature, philosophy, language, life-writing and the concept of 'Heimat' (homeland) as well as the cultural impact of the World Wars. While there is an emphasis on literary texts, other fields of cultural representation are also included.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aDeutsch-Kanadische Beziehungen. 4aGroßbritannien /Literatur, Literaturgeschichte. 4aKanada /Literarisches Motiv. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aANTOR, HEINZ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntor, Heinz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBÖLLING, GORDON, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBölling, Gordon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGLAAP, ALBERT-REINER, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHEINZE, MICHAEL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aINNES, CHRISTOPHER, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJUST, MELANIE, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKERN-STÄHLER, ANNETTE, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKern-Stähler, Annette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMCGILL, ROBERT, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMERKL, MATTHIAS, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNOWAK, ELKE, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPETERS, SUSANNE, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPROBST, INGMAR, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRICHTER, MIRIAM, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSKIDMORE, JAMES Μ ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSTIERSTORFER, KLAUS, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStierstorfer, Klaus,